=9D under=\r\nstanding of the Gayatri mantra, with the Sun as the devata. This follows th=\r\ne famous verse from the Agastya Smriti --&nbsp;=E2=80=9Cyo devaH savitA&nbs=\r\np; .asmAkam dhiyo dharmAdigocarAH. prerayet tasya yad\n bhargaH tad vareNyam=\r\n upAsmahe=E2=80=9D. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;We&nbsp;meditate upon (dhii=\r\nmahi)&nbsp;the splendor / tejas (bhargaH) of the deva (devasya) that is the=\r\n Sun (savituH).&nbsp;This tejas is the light of the sun, which is experienc=\r\ned by all living beings, and is thus easy to meditate upon.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&nbsp=\r\n;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Whatever is experienced is easy to meditate upon, and that whic=\r\nh is not experienced can be difficult to meditate upon. Everyone can medita=\r\nte upon the light of the Sun. This is why this meaning for the Gayatri mant=\r\nra is always taken first. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;vareNyam&nbsp;=3D wha=\r\ntever we can ask&nbsp;/ desire. Through all karmas and upaasanaas, whatever=\r\n fruits we may ask for is vareNyam. =E2=80=9CSavitaa&quot; is the fruit of all k=\r\narmas ... this is taught in the Chandogya Upanishad. [ A long explanation f=\r\nollows, which is omitted here ].&nbsp; We meditate upon the splendor of the=\r\n sun, which is vareNyam.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;We\n meditate upon that =\r\nSavitaa (yaH) who impels (prachodayaat) our (naH) thoughts (dhiyaH). He ble=\r\nsses us with subtle eyesight. Without his light, we would not be able to di=\r\nstinguish different objects. This is explained in the Aitaterya Upanishad&n=\r\nbsp;=E2=80=9CThe sun, having become eyesight, entered the eyes=E2=80=9D. He=\r\n thus blesses all living beings. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;----&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div=\r\n&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Sent from Windows Mail&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;=\r\n\n\n    &lt;/div&gt;\n     \n\n\n\n&lt;/div&g